{"questionId":"22567","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><strong>In this question you will explore some of the properties of special functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">g</mi></math> and their relationship with the trigonometric functions, sine and cosine.</strong></p>\n<p><br>Functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> are defined as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mi>z</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>z</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mi>z</mi></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>z</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℂ</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Consider <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>u</mi></math>, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>u</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi></math> are known as circular functions as the general point (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math>) defines points on the unit circle with equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>The functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> are known as hyperbolic functions, as the general point (&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;) defines points on a curve known as a hyperbola with equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>. This hyperbola has two asymptotes.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The hyperbola with equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> can be rotated to coincide with the curve defined by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the possible values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to rotate by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo></math> in either direction&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Evidence of an attempt to relate to a sketch of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math> would be sufficient for&nbsp;this <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em>.</p>\n<p><br>attempting to rotate a particular point, eg <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;rotates to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mo>±</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mstyle></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;(or similar)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22567","referenceCode":"21N.3.AHL.TZ0.1g","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The hyperbola with equation x2-y2=1 can be rotated to coincide with the curve defined by xy=k, k∈ℝ. Find the possible values of k.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"g","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.12—Complex numbers – Cartesian form and Argand diag","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}